# Cursor Rules for 조용한 동네 카페 Landing Page

## Project Overview
This is a pre-opening landing page for a quiet neighborhood cafe ("조용한 동네 카페") targeting local residents. The brand emphasizes calm, minimal, and comfortable spaces for solo visitors.

## Core Principles

### Brand Aesthetic
- **Quiet & Calm**: Avoid excessive animations, popups, or distracting interactions
- **Minimal & Clean**: Keep UI simple and focused on content
- **Local & Authentic**: Use honest, unexaggerated language (no trendy hype)
- **Comfortable**: Design for long stays and solo visitors

### Code Style

#### HTML

**Structure & Semantics**
- Use semantic HTML5 elements (`<header>`, `<main>`, `<section>`, `<nav>`, `<footer>`)
- Always include proper accessibility attributes:
  - `aria-label` for icon buttons
  - `aria-expanded` for toggle buttons
  - `lang="ko"` on `<html>` tag
- Use descriptive class names following BEM-like conventions (e.g., `hero-title`, `section-text`)
- Include proper meta tags for SEO and mobile viewport

**Formatting**
- Use 2 spaces for indentation
- Use double quotes for attributes
- Self-closing tags should have trailing slash: `<img />`, `<br />`
- Always include closing tags (no self-closing for HTML5 elements)
- Keep attributes on same line as opening tag if short, otherwise one per line

**Example:**
```html
<section class="section hero" id="top">
  <div class="container hero-grid">
    <div class="hero-copy">
      <h1 class="hero-title">시끄럽지 않아<br />혼자 오기 좋은 카페</h1>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
```

**Accessibility Requirements**
- All images must have `alt` attributes (or `aria-hidden="true"` for decorative images)
- Form inputs must have associated `<label>` elements
- Interactive elements must be keyboard accessible
- Use proper heading hierarchy (h1 → h2 → h3, no skipping levels)

#### CSS

**Variables & Custom Properties**
- Use CSS custom properties (CSS variables) defined in `:root` for:
  - Colors (primary, secondary, accent, text, backgrounds)
  - Typography (font-family, sizes, line-height)
  - Spacing (consistent spacing scale)
  - Breakpoints (mobile: 768px, tablet: 1024px)
  - Transitions (subtle, ~0.3s ease)
- Variable naming: `--color-*`, `--spacing-*`, `--font-*`, `--bp-*`, `--transition-*`

**Formatting**
- Use 2 spaces for indentation
- One selector per line in multi-selector rules
- One property per line
- Properties grouped logically (layout → typography → colors → effects)
- Use single quotes for strings in content/urls
- Trailing semicolon on last property

**Organization**
- Organize CSS with clear section comments using format:
  ```css
  /* ============================================
     Section Name
     ============================================ */
  ```
- Group related styles together
- Use mobile-first responsive design approach
- Media queries should be placed after base styles

**Naming Conventions**
- Use kebab-case for class names: `.hero-title`, `.section-text`
- Use descriptive, semantic names (avoid abbreviations)
- Modifier classes: `.btn-primary`, `.section-muted`
- State classes: `.active`, `.scrolled`, `.open`

**Color & Design**
- Use muted, calm color palette (avoid bright/vibrant colors)
- Always use CSS variables for colors, never hardcode hex values
- Maintain consistent spacing using the spacing scale
- Use `rem` units for spacing and typography
- Use `px` only for borders and small details

**Example:**
```css
/* ============================================
   Hero Section
   ============================================ */

.hero {
  padding: var(--spacing-xl) 0;
  background-color: var(--color-bg);
}

.hero-title {
  font-size: 2rem;
  color: var(--color-text);
  margin-bottom: var(--spacing-md);
}

@media (min-width: 768px) {
  .hero-title {
    font-size: 3rem;
  }
}
```

**Performance**
- Avoid deep nesting (max 3-4 levels)
- Use efficient selectors (avoid overly specific selectors)
- Group media queries by breakpoint when possible
- Use `transform` and `opacity` for animations (GPU accelerated)

#### JavaScript

**General Rules**
- Vanilla JavaScript only (no frameworks or libraries)
- Use modern ES6+ syntax (const, let, arrow functions, template literals)
- Use `const` by default, `let` only when reassignment is needed
- Never use `var`

**Formatting**
- Use 2 spaces for indentation
- Use single quotes for strings
- Use semicolons at end of statements
- Use trailing commas in objects and arrays
- Maximum line length: 100 characters (soft limit)

**Organization**
- Use clear section comments to organize code:
  ```javascript
  // ============================================
  // Section Name
  // ============================================
  ```
- Group related functionality together
- Declare variables at the top of their scope
- Functions should be defined before they are called

**Naming Conventions**
- Use camelCase for variables and functions: `handleScroll`, `navToggle`
- Use PascalCase only for constructors (if needed)
- Use descriptive names (avoid abbreviations)
- Boolean variables should start with `is`, `has`, `can`: `isExpanded`, `hasActiveClass`

**DOM Manipulation**
- Always check for element existence before manipulation
- Cache DOM queries in variables when reused
- Use `getElementById` for single elements, `querySelector` for complex selectors
- Use `querySelectorAll` and iterate with `forEach` for multiple elements

**Event Handling**
- Use event delegation where appropriate
- Always remove event listeners if elements are dynamically removed
- Use named functions for event handlers (better for debugging)
- Handle errors gracefully

**Accessibility**
- Update ARIA attributes when state changes
- Ensure keyboard navigation works
- Prevent default behavior only when necessary
- Maintain focus management for modals/dropdowns

**Example:**
```javascript
// ============================================
// Mobile Navigation Toggle
// ============================================

const navToggle = document.getElementById('nav-toggle');
const navList = document.getElementById('nav-list');

function toggleNav() {
  const isExpanded = navToggle.getAttribute('aria-expanded') === 'true';
  navToggle.setAttribute('aria-expanded', !isExpanded);
  navList.classList.toggle('active');
}

if (navToggle && navList) {
  navToggle.addEventListener('click', toggleNav);
}
```

**Performance**
- Debounce scroll and resize event handlers
- Use `requestAnimationFrame` for animations
- Avoid frequent DOM queries in loops
- Keep interactions subtle and non-intrusive

